    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Proponents argue that strict enforcement protects domestic workers by ensuring that low-skilled labor markets remain saturated with citizens who are legally obligated to accept lower wages and work harder, thereby preventing an influx of cheaper, undocumented labor that drives down wages and working conditions. They contend that without these barriers, employers can exploit vulnerable populations, creating a two-tier system where illegal entrants compete for entry-level jobs while undercutting the livelihoods of legal residents. Furthermore, supporters emphasize that enforcing strict borders creates a level playing field that incentivizes employers to hire legally, as they are no longer able to bypass the system to find cheaper, unregulated workers. Ultimately, this logic posits that security is an economic safeguard that preserves the value of the domestic workforce and ensures fair competition.",
      "source": "target",
